With a deep breath, I gripped the mop, set my feet shoulder-width apart, and stared at the offending mess. A faint scowl creased my brow as I pondered the carelessness of the person who'd left this mess. My hand moved toward the wall, grasping the toilet paper, and I deliberately stilled my thoughts, ready to confront the unglamorous task at hand. I dipped my hand slowly into the bowl, the unexpected intimacy of the moment a fleeting echo of a creative spark that seemed to have abandoned me.

Thanks be to the statistics.  For the past few years, we've all witnessed the alarming rise in teenage fatalities behind the wheel. Several factors converge to create this tragic trend among the youngest American drivers. The National Institutes of Health reveal that one aspect of the problem lies in the teen brain's inability to handle the perils of driving. Inexperience is another elephant in the room, causing not only deadly crashes but also a higher rate of rollovers, speeding, and vehicles veering off the road.

The statistics are even more disturbing when considering the presence of peer passengers. It's a well-known fact that teens often travel with friends, but a study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center highlights a striking correlation: the more youthful the passenger, the greater the risk of traffic accidents.

In an effort to mitigate this issue, California and other states have implemented provisional driver's licenses, limiting the hours teens can drive and prohibiting other minors as passengers. However, in my opinion, these measures are merely band-aids on a much larger problem. The real issue is that, as a group, the youngest drivers are statistically incapable of adequately managing the risks and responsibilities associated with driving. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman agrees, suggesting that 18 is still too young for a full driver's license. His research indicates that those under 19-20 years old have a strong desire to take risks for the thrill of it, making it sensible to delay driving until this tendency subsides.

If we continue to issue driver's licenses to young teens, we'll not only see more fatal accidents but the death toll will likely skyrocket in the next few years. By 2010, the Baby Boomer generation's children will come of age and millions of new teen drivers will flood the roads. 

Implementing legislation to address this issue would be straightforward. Schools could continue to offer driver's education classes to initiate the learning process, but no one under 18 should be allowed to operate a vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued before a full driver's license, with a specified number of practical driving hours required. This number could be based on the hours already mandated by most states (for instance, California requires 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult). Uniform, national legislation on this matter would be a reasonable and effective way to safeguard teens across the country.

This proposed legislation is far from novel – it's a long-overdue solution to a pressing problem.

Browsing through the Library of Congress's archives, I stumbled upon the early Edison films and decided to give them all a watch. I was particularly drawn to the trick films – there were fifteen of them, hailing from 1895 to 1901. As I delved into these films, I discovered that they relied on creative editing to create illusions. My analysis mainly focused on dissecting the poetic techniques used in most of these trick films and identifying the innovative characteristics that emerged in a few of the later ones. The trick films of the time were largely confined to a set-bound format, shot within a frontal proscenium, utilized long and medium shots, and stuck to the rule of one shot equals one film.

However, there were a few daring films at the turn of the century that broke free from these conventions by introducing new elements such as multiple shots. One thing that stood out about these trick films was their consistent use of an interior set within a frontal proscenium frame. The camera remained stationary, refusing to pan or zoom in on the action. This composition was a common trait of early films, drawing inspiration from the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. As a result, figures in these trick films were limited in their movement, typically moving side-to-side rather than forward or backward. A classic example can be seen in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), where the actors enter from the right side and move horizontally along the frame, only to disappear from view without the camera following them.

The use of the frontal proscenium style also led to a reliance on long shots and, occasionally, medium shots. Close-ups were a rarity in these trick films, adhering to the theatre and vaudeville tradition where the audience would see the entire performance within the frame. Since the actors remained in the middle ground, close-ups were never a possibility. In most early trick films, one conceptually cohesive shot equaled one physical film, limiting their length to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. This also restricted the use of tricks in storytelling, as most focused on short, vaudeville-style illusions like magic, disappearing acts, and switching tricks with minimal narrative. However, it's worth noting that in a trick film, a single "shot" can actually be composed of multiple joined shots to create an illusion of apparition or disappearance. Take The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895) for example – a closer examination reveals the moment when the physical shot of Mary's severed "head" begins, despite the entire film being conceptually one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was a true blue advocate for the Republican cause. Though his primary occupation as an agriculturalist and his brief stint in politics didn't quite add up to a long resume, they did cement his reputation as a steadfast champion of personal freedom and government restraint. His passion for an agrarian way of life was the backbone of his stance on governance, and his devotion to this cause colored his opinions on autonomy, constitutionalism, and the judicial system. He firmly believed that the United States had a unique opportunity to create a utopian system, unencumbered by the baggage of a native tradition, allowing the nation's founders to establish a system of self-governance that truly represented the people.

To Taylor, the natural rights of man were sacrosanct, and he believed that they were all interconnected - that if one right was denied, the value of the others would be diminished. He argued that these rights should be beyond the reach of the government, which he saw as prone to abuse by those with physical prowess and malicious intent. In his view, the so-called "state of nature" was a harsh reality, but one that should be mitigated by the establishment of a civilization that valued fairness and justice over might and greed.

To achieve this ideal society, Taylor believed that a government must be constructed to account for the dual nature of humanity - both good and evil. He was unwavering in his conviction that government would always reflect the virtues and vices of its people. According to him, good principles were those that protected private property, fostered agriculture, and discouraged unchecked capitalism, and a government founded on these principles would function equitably, regardless of who was at the helm. However, self-interest, which he saw as the driving force behind human behavior, was only a problem when it prioritized individual gain over the common good.

Taylor, like many of his fellow Republicans, was a staunch advocate for a strict construction of the Constitution, with a Federal government that possessed only the powers explicitly granted to it by the document. He believed that a limited government was inherently more efficient and less prone to tyranny, but also warned that a literal interpretation of the Constitution without regard for its original intent was a recipe for disaster. Furthermore, he saw the Declaration of Independence as the true charter of the United States, as it more explicitly enshrined the sovereignty of individual states rather than a unified nation.

Looking at Figure 17, we noticed a dramatic decline in commuter log submissions in the third month of our project. It was a bit disheartening and we're still trying to figure out what caused it. Winter is probably to blame, at least in part, as folks on our New England campus are less likely to bike or walk during the cold months. Then there's the end of the fall semester, which keeps everyone busy with schoolwork, grades, and more, making it easy to overlook the commuter log. The holiday season also sets in around December, with a long break for students and faculty, so it's no surprise that many people don't need to come to campus that month. We do see a lull in activity after the break, which resumes in late January. But, we still can't explain the low number of submissions in February. Perhaps it's just the natural ebb and flow of a project, where the initial excitement eventually wears off. To combat this, we launched the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special campaign that got people back on board and resulted in a spike in log submissions that month. Our challenge, however, was to maintain momentum despite the inevitable decrease in engagement, as well as the holiday and semester breaks that come with higher education. 

Another obstacle we faced (and one that's inherent in any alternative commuting project) is that people love the freedom, independence, and flexibility that comes with driving their own cars. It's deeply ingrained in our culture, making it essential to offer incentives for switching to alternative modes of transportation. We offered a range of prizes, from gift certificates to local restaurants and coffee shops to massages and bookstore discounts. It would have been interesting to see how bigger prizes, like a nice bicycle or a hybrid car, might have affected participation. Perhaps if we'd offered increasingly valuable prizes throughout the project, we could have prevented that dip in engagement. Our prize offerings remained the same throughout, but if we'd announced bigger and better prizes, like a bicycle in December and a hybrid car in January, we might have seen participation and engagement increase instead of decrease.

I'm still getting used to the wild world of exchange-traded funds (ETFs), but one thing's for sure - they're a game-changer. Essentially, an ETF is like a security that tracks an index, commodity, or basket of assets, just like an index fund, but with a twist: it trades like a stock on an exchange. This means you get the benefits of diversification, like owning a piece of every stock in the fund, without the hassle of individually managing each one. Plus, you can sell short, buy on margin, or even purchase as few as a single share in any transaction. And the best part? The expense ratios of ETFs are often significantly lower than those of the average mutual fund. However, there are some downsides to consider, such as paying a commission on each trade, just like when buying or selling individual stocks. 

But with the sheer variety of ETFs available, it can be overwhelming to choose the right one. That's why it's essential for savvy investors to evaluate whether the touted benefits, like diversification, actually live up to the hype. In this case, we're taking a closer look at the ETF IHF and comparing it to its top 10 holdings to see if owning a single ETF is worth it. We'll also examine whether a portfolio of these 10 stocks can provide similar benefits to a diversified portfolio of the same stocks. To keep things manageable, we're focusing on the top 10 holdings, which account for a whopping 63.58% of the ETF's assets.

To gauge how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF as a whole, we've calculated their contributions to the portfolio's beta and return, assuming a portfolio made up entirely of these stocks in the same proportions as the ETF. The results are telling: a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings would yield a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, representing a 16% increase in returns. What's more, the beta of this portfolio is 0.12 lower than the ETF's, suggesting a potentially more stable investment. However, there's a chance that these results might not be statistically significant.

To get a better understanding of the data, we've also calculated the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks, normalized to 100% to compare them to the ETF IHF. This will give us insight into the potential risks and rewards of investing in these stocks, and whether a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings is a viable alternative to the ETF.

I've always been fascinated by Edgar Allan Poe's "Dream-Land," one of his self-proclaimed masterpieces. The poem's use of the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56 is particularly intriguing. My research led me to Virgil, who first used the term to describe an island north of Britain, believed to be the edge of the known world. However, there's a more contemporary source that sheds light on Poe's familiarity with German authors. Poe was indeed enamored with Goethe's writing.

This connection is significant because it highlights Poe's influence from Goethe. As Karl J. Arndt notes in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," Poe's poem bears a striking resemblance to Goethe's work, suggesting that Poe may have been drawing inspiration from the German author. 

Oxford Companion to English Literature credits Goethe as a celebrated writer of the poetic drama "Faust," which was published in two parts, with the first installment coming out in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of Goethe's passing. Within the second part of "Faust," there's a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." This poem tells the story of a king whose wife gives him a goblet before her untimely death. The king's descent into grief and despair is marked by excessive drinking, and he ultimately decides to join his wife in death.

The similarity between the King of Thule and the character in "Dream-Land" is striking, with both figures being haunted by loss and finding solace in drink. Interestingly, Goethe's "Faust" was adapted into a romantic drama by H.P. Grattan in 1842, just a year before Poe's use of the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum." 

Poe references Thule twice in his collected works, using the phrase "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and employing it as a bookend in "Dream-Land." When read alongside Goethe's "The King of Thule," the two poems can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes a desolate landscape of Thule, marked by darkness, loneliness, and a world devoid of color. This echoes the King of Thule's story, who has lost his will to live after the passing of his wife.

Given Poe's admiration for Tennyson, it's likely that he would have been familiar with Goethe's work. Poe's statement on Tennyson aside, it's clear that he would have been exposed to Goethe's writing through various reproductions and adaptations that followed the original publication.

Here's the juicy stuff that could help a customer injured from slipping on an applesauce spill in a grocery store get a hefty chunk of change from the store manager.  I'm talking punitive damages, baby - the kind that can make someone's wallet weep. So, under California law, is this possible? Can Jennifer Palmer, the injured party, show that the store manager, Paul Martin, acted with malice when he ignored the spill for a whole half-hour because he was too busy eating dinner? 

Rest assured, a judge won't dismiss her claim without a fight. To win punitive damages, Palmer needs to show that Martin recklessly disregarded the harm that could come from not cleaning up the spill. She can argue that the manager should have known better since multiple customers had slipped on the same spot in the months leading up to her accident. And let's not forget, he still didn't do squat to fix it despite all those prior incidents.

Now, some might say Palmer's argument about Martin's actions being despicable is a bit of a stretch, but it's not entirely unreasonable given the facts. Six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009 and no action taken to prevent them? That's just not cool.

Let's take a trip down memory lane. On October 13th, 2009, around 5 pm, an employee, Rich Wayne, told Martin about the applesauce spill, but he blew him off, saying he was on dinner break. Another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also warned Martin about the spill 15 minutes later, but he gave her the same brush-off. Guess who slipped and fell on the spill at 5:30 pm? That's right, Jennifer Palmer, and she ended up with a serious back injury. It's no wonder she's suing D&D Markets for compensatory and punitive damages.

In California, if a defendant acts with "oppression, fraud or malice," a plaintiff can win punitive damages for a breach of obligation not arising from a contract. The law defines malice as conduct intended to cause harm or, if no intent, the defendant's actions were so bad that they demonstrate a "willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." So, was Martin's inaction a malicious act? Did he know the probable harm that could come from not cleaning up the spill, and did he deliberately ignore it? According to the courts, a defendant's actions are malicious if they knew the likely consequences of their actions and chose to ignore them.

In this case, the courts might just decide that Martin's actions were indeed malicious, and Palmer could be on her way to a fat check. But we're not there yet. It's time to see if we should file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim. Stay tuned!

It's been almost four years since I took a course in Islam at CBC, and the topic of whether Islam is a hostile religion remains a pressing issue.  I firmly believe that this question is more relevant now than ever, especially considering the media's shift in perspective since 9/11.  I recall the way the media used to portray Islam and extremists as hostile entities, only to swing to the opposite end of the spectrum and become excessively tolerant of Islam in America.  It's hard to imagine that in 2001, a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, with an openly Muslim background, could have even been considered viable.

The Biography of the Prophet Muhammad has left me with a compelling narrative that contradicts the man I thought I knew from history.  According to my understanding, Muhammad was supposed to be a figure who forced people to convert to Islam after conquering tribes and imposing his rule.  However, the biography paints a completely different picture – that of a humble, misunderstood, and humbled individual who was shunned by others but ultimately drew followers who saw the truth in his teachings.  This portrayal has left me questioning the validity of the history I thought I knew.

The parallels between the ministries of Jesus and the supposed miracles of Muhammad are remarkable.  One of the most striking examples is the story of feeding forty men with a small amount of mutton and milk, which seems eerily similar to Jesus' miracle of feeding the multitudes.  It's this type of writing that makes me suspect the authors were trying to portray Muhammad as a humble prophet who didn't need to prove anything, but lived a life of truth and miracles.  This approach undermines the significance of Jesus' life and ministry, making it seem like a pale imitation.

I also find it interesting that the biography features many stories that aim to provide proof of 'witness' or show how people converted to Islam of their own accord.  However, these stories often rely on third-party accounts, which diminish their credibility in my eyes.  While the authors intended to provide evidence of the truth, it only makes the stories seem more suspect and less authentic.

What bothers me most about this work is the attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly figure, portraying him as humble, endearing, wise, and gentle.  History, however, contradicts this image, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true story behind Muhammad's rise to power.

As Christianity progressed beyond its roots, the teachings of Jesus and the core beliefs he held during his lifetime were cast aside in favor of a more developed theory. When viewed from a broad perspective, a pattern emerges of Christianity gradually straying further and further from its authentic origin. Today, an increasing awareness and a shift towards progression are underway, revealing a growing desire for a return to the true essence of the faith. While traditionalists may cling to established doctrine, they may not be numerous enough to influence the broader masses. As time passes, however, a historical awareness will grow among Christians, driving a yearning to distinguish between the original intent of Christianity and the doctrines that were added over time. This reversal of trends will eventually lead to a movement that sheds its accumulated layers, gradually stripping away the extraneous to reveal the pure essence of Jesus' original message. A gradual clock-like motion will be seen as people return to the core principles Jesus instilled, untainted by the additions of subsequent thinkers.  As this forward-thinking movement sweeps through the United States and Europe, expect to see a shift from the current divergence towards a more uniform and cohesive understanding of the faith. The church, as an institution, will remain a guiding force, but the turbulent diversity of Christendom will give way to increased uniformity across regions, denominations, and divisions. History is replete with examples of such reversals – consider how Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, only to see the empire eventually adopt Christianity. Similarly, the United States transitioned from slavery to African-American leadership. In the future, Christianity will undergo a profound reversal, undoing the accumulated history in the quest for its authentic roots, and in the process, shedding its diversity. A crucial aspect of this shift will be reinterpreting Jesus' words as metaphorical rather than literal statements. Looking back, we find the seeds of Christianity in Judaism, which flourished as a divinely revealed, monotheistic faith before the Roman Empire's control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not a homogeneous entity; it was fragmented into various groups, including the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the common folk.

As I reflect on the timeless classic, The Jungle, I'm struck by the harsh reality that deep down, humans are often driven by self-interest and a desire for personal gain, leaving those in lower positions to fend for themselves. This is starkly illustrated in the novel, particularly through the lens of the factory owners and managers. Their only concern is to expand and thrive, no matter the cost to others or the environment. They're depicted as callous and ruthless, with no regard for the devastating impact of their actions, as Upton Sinclair masterfully conveys through the vivid image of the factories' towering chimneys belching smoke into the air, symbolizing the destruction they cause. The owners and managers show no empathy for the harm their endeavors inflict on the people and animals living in the shadows of Packingtown, nor do they care about the well-being of their employees, whom they treat as nothing more than means to an end. They're driven by a relentless pursuit of profit, as Sinclair so poignantly puts it: "So from top to bottom, this place is a seething cauldron of jealousy and hatred, devoid of loyalty and decency, where a man is nothing more than a commodity to be exploited for a dollar." During the era in which the book is set, workers were at the mercy of their employers, forced to toil in inhumane conditions with little to no protection or support. The system was designed to prioritize profit over people, leaving workers to suffer and struggle in a desperate fight for survival. The novel suggests that the workers were, in effect, treated as slaves, their lives hanging in the balance of their employers' whims, with no escape from the crushing system of Packingtown.

Many authors employ various tactics to evoke a particular sentiment or attitude in their readers. The effectiveness of these techniques can vary, but F. Scott Fitzgerald masterfully weaves them throughout his novel, The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs seemingly mismatched adjectives and nouns to conjure a specific atmosphere around a subject. He also assigns meaning to symbols and later utilizes them to convey a particular mood. This technique is particularly evident in his use of colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink.

In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald meticulously builds up associations for white/gray, then skillfully employs them to elicit a certain response from his readers. The significance he attributes to white/gray is uniformity, with white generally representing a more refined and upper-class connotation, while gray carries a sense of age and faded elegance. Fitzgerald sets the stage for these meanings early in the novel through repeated references to both colors. We see this in the way Daisy and Jordan are constantly "in white" (8) – everyone, it seems, is donning white attire: Nick sports "white flannels" (41) at Gatsby's party, Tom wears a "white shirt" (36) when meeting Myrtle, and Catherine is "powdered milky white" (30). The only time white attire is absent is during Nick's initial impressions of Gatsby's party, where the halls are "gaudy with primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald further defines these colors by associating them with everyday, mundane subjects: as Nick heads to work, he navigates "the white chasms of lower New York" (56), the names of people at Gatsby's parties become "gray names" (61) on Nick's timetable, and Catherine's apartment is likened to "one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses" – epitomizing uniformity.

Fitzgerald then uses these established meanings to convey a sense of unimportance or uniformity in certain subjects. This process begins with Daisy. After a prolonged period without significant use of white/gray, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster"; readers start to perceive Daisy as less of a distinct character and more of a uniform entity, a mere aspiration for Gatsby (74). Fitzgerald employs this technique repeatedly to reinforce this impression of Daisy as a uniform addition, as seen in the "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" (18) and her appearance in a "white" (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

The San Diego County is a veritable garden of plenty, thanks to its sun-kissed climate that makes it an ideal place for agriculture. The region is blessed with a diverse array of crops, including tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There's a thriving market for organic community supported agriculture food in the area, with many local organizations boasting lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand, and some farms even offer tours of their operations, along with opportunities for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This type of farming operation allows landowners to tap into government programs while preserving the land's natural beauty, creating a win-win situation for both the environment and their bank accounts.

However, organic farming isn't without its challenges. It requires more labor and management to maintain soil health without relying on chemicals, which can lead to greater costs and losses compared to conventional farming methods. Small organic farms often lack the efficiency of large-scale operations, making it harder to compete in the market. Other practices that benefit wildlife, such as planting cover crops and removing invasive species, also incur additional labor costs. As a result, landowners in this scenario might seek financial assistance or expert guidance to maximize their profits while preserving the land's biodiversity.

The chosen property is a 160-acre plot adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. The land is a mix of chaparral, non-native grassland, and oak woodland, nestled next to the Cleveland National Forest within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. This plan, still under review, aims to protect over a hundred plant and animal species, many of which are endangered or declining, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, and several butterfly species. The area has a rich history, having been inhabited by Native Americans for centuries before being settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This particular piece of land was likely used for grazing and wood production for many years, given its original homestead patent status.

To explore the options available to a small farmer in this area, I chose a property from a real estate website and researched government programs that could help mitigate costs and support wildlife-friendly farming practices. As a model for what someone farming this land might aim to achieve, I looked at an existing organic farm in the same region.

The intricacies of culture play a pivotal role in any negotiation, but they're often misunderstood or oversimplified. Culture is a complex web of nuances that can be just as easily defined by what it's not as by what it is. It's not a monolith, nor is it uniform or one-dimensional. Statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are woefully broad and reductive. A more productive approach for a negotiator is to grasp the significance of a culture in relation to the specific issue at hand and how its attitude will impact the negotiations. When engaging with a foreign culture, we inevitably view it through the lens of our own, and comparisons inevitably arise. 

Delving into a foreign culture often requires a multidisciplinary approach, encompassing everything from historical context to understanding its biases. Rather than judging or trying to change a culture, it's essential to accept it for what it is and navigate its boundaries, particularly in high-stakes negotiations where a weaker bargaining position is at play. When operating in unfamiliar territory, a deep respect for local traditions and customs can be a game-changer in breaking down cultural barriers and moving the negotiation forward.

It's a common misconception that culture is solely bound by national or international borders. In reality, many companies within a given nation have their own distinct corporate cultures that can be just as influential as any national culture. This can manifest in everything from dress codes and communication styles to hiring practices and employee values. Even within the United States, corporate cultures vary wildly from company to company, and within companies, there are often regional and urban-suburban differences that showcase the diversity of thought within a particular societal culture. Don't be fooled by a uniform exterior – it's often a sign to dig deeper.

Values are the key to understanding the underlying dynamics of a culture. If a culture places a high value on saving face or communal harmony, a negotiator will likely avoid publicly embarrassing their company or superior in pursuit of a deal. Conversely, a culture that prioritizes driving a hard bargain won't necessarily be willing to settle at the earliest opportunity. By considering these cultural nuances before the negotiating table, you'll be better equipped to navigate the complexities of cross-cultural negotiation. But it's equally important to learn about your opponent on a personal level to make the negotiation a success.

We often hear the phrase, "The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God,'" which originates in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and is famously referenced by St. Anselm in his argument for the existence of God. Interestingly, Thomas Aquinas seems to share this sentiment, and as we delve into their arguments, it's worth assuming they're both correct in their belief, specifically in the God of the Bible. If we were to consider a different concept of God, it would skew our comparison, as their arguments are centered around a particular idea of the divine. Therefore, let's begin by accepting their shared premise for the sake of clarity.

While both authors bring up valid points, neither provides a comprehensive foundation for faith in God. To illustrate this, let's break down St. Anselm's basic argument. He suggests that understanding and proof of God can be found within ourselves, through introspection and faith. According to Anselm, because our minds inherently grasp the concept of God, we can't effectively conceive of his nonexistence. On the surface, this idea might be wordy and unclear, but in essence, Anselm is saying that the truth about God is within our own minds and doesn't require external evidence. This concept of accepting the truth without empirical proof is often referred to as faith in Christian texts.

In stark contrast, St. Thomas Aquinas proposes that God's existence can be proven solely through reason and empirical evidence, eliminating the need for faith altogether. This idea would be beneficial in evangelism, as it would allow for the recruitment of new converts based on logic rather than blind faith. Aquinas presents five logical arguments supporting God's existence: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for his existence. Think of it like this: if you're told you're missing a puzzle piece and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can infer the features and existence of the missing piece without seeing it.

Twenty-five hundred years ago, a prince destined to become the revered figure known as Buddha was born. Throughout the course of his life, he renounced worldly pursuits and achieved enlightenment, paving the way for the emergence of Buddhism. This ancient faith has undergone significant transformations since its inception, a phenomenon evident in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is an integral part of the culture. Despite the fact that Buddha never preached about such festivities, this event brings together monks and laypeople alike, reflecting the dynamic evolution of the religion. From superficial customs to its fundamental tenets, the Theravada Buddhist community has had to adapt its principles over time. This metamorphosis can be attributed to factors both within and outside the Buddhist fold, encompassing a range of influences, from the benign to the hostile.

To facilitate this discussion, it's essential to understand the key terms that will be used throughout. Internally, an internal force refers to any influence originating from within the Buddhist community, regardless of one's monastic status. Conversely, an external force is any influence stemming from non-Buddhists. As for hostile and benign forces, a hostile force is any influence that seeks to harm or damage the Buddhist community, often driven by a negative perception of the faith. A benign force, on the other hand, is an influence that neither wishes to harm nor help the community, though it might inadvertently do so.

Now, let's delve into the core of Theravada Buddhism, exploring the fundamental doctrines that form its foundation. At the heart of the faith lies the concept of the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma encompasses the Tripitaka, a collection of sacred texts divided into three baskets: the Sutta Pitaka (containing the Suttas), the Vinaya Pitaka (outlining disciplinary rules), and the Abhidhamma Pitaka (dealing with metaphysical concepts). Central to these metaphysical notions are the principles of Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering in life), and Anicca (the impermanence of everything). Recognizing these concepts holds the key to breaking free from Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, and ultimately transcending lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). In the Vinaya Pitaka, guidelines for daily life are established, with five precepts for laypeople (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not engage in misconduct, and I shall not consume intoxicating substances) and additional disciplinary rules for monks. At the heart of Buddhism lies the four noble truths, a fundamental doctrine that encompasses the reality of suffering (Dukkha), the causes of suffering (attachment), and the possibility of overcoming suffering.

For over five decades, the United States and Mexico were locked in a bitter rivalry that would leave a lasting impact on their relationship. From 1836 to 1893, tensions simmered between the two nations, with the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848 being the turning point. This conflict saw the United States emerge victorious, claiming Texas and the American Southwest as its own. However, clashes between the two nations continued to erupt over the years, finally dying down just before the outbreak of World War I.

At its core, the rivalry between the United States and Mexico was fueled by deep-seated differences over issues like religion, culture, and tradition. Material interests also played a significant role in exacerbating the tensions between the two nations. It's a pattern we see repeated in many other rivalries between nations that share a border, where clashing interests inevitably lead to the development of opposing positions.

David M. Pletcher noted that the United States had long-standing diplomatic issues with two countries in particular: Mexico and Cuba. Given their geographical proximity to the United States, it's no surprise that these nations have historically found themselves at odds with America. In contrast, many other Latin American countries have enjoyed more harmonious relations with the United States.

The religious divide between the United States and Mexico was a significant factor in their rivalry. Sally Frahm pointed out that Americans were long opposed to Catholicism and monarchy, which created a deep-seated distrust between the two nations. This ideological struggle was reminiscent of the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, but in this case, the stakes were tied to religious differences rather than politics. The lingering effects of English-Spanish animosity only served to further complicate the relationship between the two nations.

According to Diehl and Goerts, there were 17 notable disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry period. Many of these disputes centered on territorial issues, including border raids and frontier problems. Bandits and outlaws from both sides of the border posed a major challenge that wasn't fully addressed until both countries deployed military force to secure their borders.

As Schmitt noted, the rivalry between the United States and Mexico finally began to dissipate as Mexico became increasingly dependent on its northern neighbor. The shift in American ambitions from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico marked the beginning of a new era in their relationship, one that would eventually lead to a more peaceful and cooperative relationship between the two nations.

Fifteen years ago, my life took an unexpected detour when a mysterious illness struck, leaving me disabled and out of the workforce. I was a nurse, a career I had chosen for its stability after hearing the constant mantra in my youth: "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." My true passions lay in science and journalism, but I opted for nursing to ensure a secure future. 

Now, at 46, I'm single, with nothing to show for it, relying on Social Security Disability for survival. It's a daily struggle, a relentless assault on my sense of security, safety, and self-worth. Yet, amidst this chaos, I've come to realize that the one constant in my life is the unwavering support of my family and a handful of true friends. When disaster hits, you're not as invincible as you think. 

My point is that life is full of unexpected challenges, big and small. No matter how well-prepared you are, some storms are too intense to weather alone. 

While it's essential to take responsibility for our own lives, I strongly believe we need to shift our focus from solely relying on the government to learning to trust and support one another. Rather than building individual shelters, we should strive to build a community where neighbors look out for each other. 

The concept of rugged individualism, often touted by Conservatives, is a myth. It was compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources that saw our ancestors through the tough times, not self-reliance. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it alone; they worked together.

By all means, be prepared. I've invested in a disaster kit, first-aid supplies, and other essentials. If you have the means, consider starting a small farm or investing in a wood stove. However, don't overlook the most vital survival tool of all – building strong relationships with those around you. Get to know your neighbors, and together, you'll be better equipped to face life's uncertainties.

We often ponder the enigma of why organisms evolve in the manner that they do. Are there unseen forces at play that shape the course of evolutionary change? While D'Arcy Thompson astutely observed in 1917 that the task of defining organic forms in mathematical terms was still a distant dream, we're still far from grasping this complexity today. However, recent advances in mathematical modeling have begun to shed light on the intricacies of mollusk development, particularly in the realm of skeletogenesis (Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research seeks to leverage mathematical modeling, in tandem with experimental studies, to unravel the underlying mechanisms driving the direction and magnitude of evolutionary change in Prunum.

To achieve this, we're examining how X-radiographic images of Prunum species can be used to quantify parameters that can then be input into software programs like CerioShell (Stone, 1995) to model hypothetical and actual shell morphologies. These models enable us to explore the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum, providing a framework for understanding macroevolutionary events within this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a spiral tube that traverses 360 degrees of space over time. This spiral path is composed of whorls, which are formed by the animal's growth and are considered to be centered around an imaginary axis, known as the columella. The speed at which each whorl enlarges can vary, and a continuous line separating each whorl is referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the body whorl, while the spire consists of all the whorls except the last. The apex, or tip, of the spire marks the beginning, while the base represents the opposite end. The animal emerges from its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed from different perspectives, including apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. Typically, shells are depicted in apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upwards.

To count whorls accurately, one must first view the shell from the apical perspective and identify the starting point of the first suture. A line can then be drawn, dividing the shell into two parts, and whorls can be counted from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that unfold through time and space as the animal adds to its shell. By tracing the path of the aperture using the center coordinates of each whorl's aperture and its horizontal and vertical radius, we can create a mathematical representation of this trajectory. This mathematical formulation enables us to manipulate parameters and modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

I've been pondering the stark reality of neonatal and infant mortality rates in Indonesia, which have remained stubbornly stagnant for a decade. As the country makes strides in meeting Millennium Development Goals such as water and sanitation targets, its progress in child and maternal health lags woefully behind. The reasons for this disappointing trend are multifaceted and point to a pressing need to fortify the overall health system rather than relying on piecemeal interventions.

Indonesia has made some progress in increasing the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with a commendable 72% now meeting this benchmark. However, this statistic is somewhat misleading, as it still includes traditional workers like midwives who are unable to provide medical interventions in complicated cases, leading to a disproportionate number of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage. Furthermore, there's been a concerning decline in the percentage of children under five receiving treatment for diarrheal cases from a health professional, and data on postnatal care is woefully inadequate.

Another worrisome trend is the relatively low cesarian-section rate of around 4%, which is compounded by the stark disparities between urban and rural areas – 7% in cities versus a paltry 2% in rural regions. This stark contrast highlights the issue of unequal access to healthcare services, with urban areas receiving preferential treatment. Vertical equity is another concern, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, suggesting that the poor are facing significant barriers in accessing healthcare due to out-of-pocket costs.

As we consider the next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the fundamental question is how to address the chronic shortage of services. Should Indonesia focus on developing targeted programmatic approaches or strengthen its overall health system without pandering to the specific needs of pre and post-pregnancy care for mothers and their children? While programmatic approaches may seem attractive, they have their drawbacks. For instance, investing heavily in one area can divert resources away from other critical areas, leading to a brain drain of human resources and duplication of services. This not only wastes resources but also creates an administrative nightmare with excessive forms and paperwork.

Victorian novels are infamous for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the lives of the aristocracy of the time.  However, two novels that break away from this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights.  Both works incorporate an air of mystery and an affinity for the bizarre, traits that were uncommon in novels of the period, but which serve to strengthen the characters within each story, offering a deeper look into their motivations and emotions.

As Oliver Twist navigated the treacherous world of Victorian London, a maelstrom of bewildering ideas swirled inside his mind. The echoes of his encounters with Sikes and Crackit lingered, their voices arguing in his ears, while his own thoughts struggled to regain focus. The sound of gunfire shattered the silence, and Oliver was swept up in a whirlwind of confusion as unseen forces bore him away. Amidst the chaos, a gnawing sense of pain and discomfort gnawed at him, refusing to let him escape.

In Oliver Twist, these unsettling occurrences often manifest as dream sequences or dreamlike states, revealing hidden facets of Oliver's psyche and the turmoil that wracked his inner world. When Oliver relives the moment of his near-fatal shooting in chapter 28, the scene unfolds with a dreamlike quality, as if he's reliving the trauma all over again while desperately seeking help. This passage highlights Oliver's powerlessness in the face of the events that have unfolded, and the dire state of his health, which is reflected in his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself overwhelms him, numbing all his senses as an unseen force bears him away, leaving him to relive his despair in a state of constant fear rather than shock. This event raises questions about whose actions led to his misfortune, as it's clear that Oliver's fate was not of his own making. The scene also implies a growing sense of defeat in Oliver, as if Fagin's influence has broken him, forcing him to accept his despair and rendering him unable to react.

The passage from Wuthering Heights reads like a haunting refrain: "The day passed – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours." This sense of time's fluidity, where day and night blur into one another, creates a sense of disorientation, underscoring the turmoil that pervades the story. The passage speaks to the novel's use of time as a fluid, malleable concept, where the boundaries between reality and fantasy blur, and the characters are left to navigate the uncertainties of their own lives.

I still remember my time working in an after-school program, where I was tasked with tutoring elementary students in a variety of subjects, but my true passion lay in helping them with reading and English. One student in particular, a young boy named Adrian, really stood out to me. He was around third or fourth grade, and I was assigned to work with him because he was struggling to read. What struck me as peculiar was that some letters he could pronounce flawlessly, while others left him completely stumped – it was as if he was speaking a different language. Given that he was Latino, I assumed that might be the issue, but his English was spotless. I spent many sessions with him, trying to figure out the problem, until the day his mother walked into the room. Her only language was Spanish, and I attempted to communicate with her using my limited Spanish skills. It was a defining moment – I realized that Adrian's struggles weren't about reading, but rather, he didn't know the English alphabet. I hope he's found success since then.

Sharing this story highlights the complex issue of the language barrier in schools, especially here in California. It's a problem that's often overlooked, but it's not always as straightforward as we think. Even a child who speaks perfect English can struggle with reading, as I learned with Adrian. We all agree that this issue exists, so what's the solution? In Adrian's case, it was as simple as extra English reading tutoring, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for students who barely speak English, it's a much more complex problem.

There's no single answer, but rather a combination of approaches that work together. The dual language system is a great concept, not just for kids who speak Spanish as their first language, but for all children. Research shows that students in two-way bilingual education programs outperform their peers academically. Many people fear that this system is a waste of resources, but it's not true. If we implemented this approach as a standard, all children would benefit from it. So, how do we make this happen? Do we require teachers to be bilingual? That's unrealistic, but we can hire bilingual aids, tutors, or whatever we want to call them, to support our students.

From the time we're young, many of us are taught that there's something greater than ourselves, something that transcends our understanding. Some of us are sent to Sunday school, while others seek answers within themselves or explore the spiritual paths our parents have laid out for us. Some accept these teachings without question, while others reject them entirely, choosing to forge their own paths. We might adopt one set of values, only to later discard them for another. Ultimately, our search for meaning leads us down a winding road to discover a part of ourselves through our unique perspectives on spirituality, seeking a guiding light to lead us out of the darkness and into the light.

[The memory of that rainy evening still lingers.] My dad and I sat on our front porch, listening to the rain drum against the tin roof above. We both smoked cigarettes, lost in our own thoughts. The rainwater pouring from the gutters drowned the plants at the edge of the porch, and my dad's eyes gazed out into the downpour, a mix of introspection and distant recollection. His frame seemed smaller, his clothes hanging loosely, and his hair was thinner than I remembered. That's when I realized he was struggling – and I was struggling too. I couldn't bring myself to talk about how much I'd miss him, as acknowledging it would make it all too real. Instead, I hugged him, sat down beside him, and joined him in gazing out into the rain.

My dad passed away that December, just five days before my twenty-second birthday. The treatments had prolonged his suffering, but at what cost? I couldn't fathom it. As I lay alone in the dark, I didn't pray. If a higher power existed, I thought, it had long since stopped listening to me. 

I refused to watch him slip away. I chose to remember my dad through his life, not his final moments. I knew him better than anyone, and I was certain he wouldn't have wanted me to be there for his passing. I curled up in my bed for three days, waiting for the news. And yet, no one even called.

The Gothic Novel: A Timeless Contradiction 
I still chuckle when I think about Ian Watt's clever description of the Gothic Novel as an 'oxymoron for Old-New.' It was as if he was trying to capture the essence of this peculiar literary beast that has been both revered and ridiculed throughout history. Critics have attacked the Gothic genre for lacking depth, yet praised it for its ability to evoke the 'terrible sublime.' (Burke) The genre has been around since the 18th century, when Horace Walpole first penned The Castle of Otranto, a true pioneer in the proto-Gothic genre. By combining the 'old' theatrical elements of medieval romances with the 'new' novelistic format, Walpole created something entirely new - a Gothic Story. 

As I delve into the world of Gothic literature, I notice how it often relies on throwbacks to medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. It was a time when the word 'gothic' was used to describe everything from people to styles to time periods, often with a hint of nostalgia and a dash of disdain for the 'modern' world. It's fascinating to see how Walpole merged the grandeur of the Gothic with the intimacy of the novel, creating a reading experience that feels both ancient and modern. 

One of the key aspects of Gothic literature that has captured my attention is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval idea of training a proper knight is woven throughout the original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is particularly significant in Gothic writing because it represents a bygone era of bravery, honor, and competence - an era that many writers, like Walpole, felt was sadly lacking in their own time. By romanticizing the 'gothic past,' writers like Walpole aimed to critique their own society and, perhaps, even hint at the future evolution of Gothic to Romanticism. 

As I read through The Castle of Otranto, I'm struck by the character of Frederic, a prince who embodies many chivalric traits. His description is a masterclass in Gothic tropes: a prince, a victim of tragedy, and a man shrouded in mystery. The image of the 'gallant and courteous Knight' is exaggerated, of course, but it's a perfect example of how excess was used to create a sense of drama and tension in the Gothic genre. As I ponder the complexities of Gothic literature, I'm reminded that even in its contradictions, there's a timeless beauty to be found.

I've witnessed the evolution of supply chain management, a world of intricate processes that weaves together raw materials, production, and distribution to meet the ever-changing demands of customers. The term supply chain management was coined by Keith Oliver in 1982, a consultant with an eye for efficiency. Oliver described the delicate dance of planning, implementing, and controlling the supply chain to deliver customer satisfaction in a swift and seamless manner. 

At the heart of supply chain management lies six essential elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. These building blocks enable business managers to craft an experience that leaves customers wanting more. 

Production is the foundation upon which the entire supply chain stands. It's the stage where the 'when,' 'why,' 'where,' and 'how' of product creation are carefully laid out. Managers must tune in to the market to grasp what customers crave. The market is the barometer that indicates the customer's desires, and by analyzing it, managers can decide what products to produce, how many to produce, and where to produce them. The goal is to meet customer demands while ensuring the best quality and volume.

Once production is underway, managers focus on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Every detail is crucial in this process, and mishaps can cost the company dearly in the long run. I've seen firsthand how having a clear process in place can make all the difference at companies like Wal-Mart and Target, where every aspect of the business, from employee attire to shipment reception, is meticulously planned.

Supply is the second vital element in the supply chain equation. It involves strategic decisions about a company's core capabilities and outsourcing partnerships. Managers must decide which divisions of production are best suited for specific products, taking into account the equipment, personnel, and specialties required. Outsourcing work to other companies can be a smart move, as it enables the creation of velocity – the ability to deliver quality, flexibility, and low costs.

A haunting message lurks on a street corner, Ellen Page's cardboard sign held high, the Sharpie-written words 'Hitler is alive in Burma' a stark reality check. Burma, now Myanmar, has been under the iron grip of a ruthless military junta since 1962, when the country was seized through a brutal coup d'état. The echoes of 2007 still linger, when a wave of protests swept the nation, known as the Saffron Revolution, in honor of the saffron-colored robes worn by the courageous Burmese monks who led the charge. What began as peaceful gatherings soon turned into a bloody conflict, with the military junta unleashing its wrath on monasteries and foreign journalists, including Japanese photojournalist Kenji Nagai, who fell to their brutality on September 27th, 2007. The official death toll may be 13, but defector Colonel Hla Win revealed a chilling truth: the real number of victims could be in the thousands.

This isn't a relic of the past. The world has been witnessing this tragic tale for millennia, as governments pursue power and silence dissent with ruthless abandon. From ancient Roman emperors claiming divine right to rule, to Japanese emperors deified as gods, to our own modern-day leaders who seem to answer to none, this dark chapter has been etched in human history. We see echoes of Tiananmen Square in 1989, where students, intellectuals, and labor activists dared to challenge the authorities, and the death toll may never be known for certain – 200 to 3,000, depending on who you believe. The Rwandan genocide, Hitler's Third Reich, and countless other atrocities serve as grim reminders of the horrors that unfold when governments turn against their own people.

The unyielding legacy of Duke Ellington in the realm of jazz can be attributed in large part to his remarkable longevity and the boundless creative influence he exerted through his orchestra. Although his piano presence is understated in many of the compositions selected for this particular task, as a composer Ellington masterfully crafted complex, rich pieces that showcased the unique talents of individual band members. He skillfully wove the framework, allowing soloists to improvise freely, while also penning tightly orchestrated phrases that highlighted the distinct styles of his musicians. In doing so, Ellington successfully emphasized the ensemble's overall tone, creating original and coherent sounds to match each piece. Through his profound understanding of the individual players' sounds and how they blended together to form a cohesive unit, Ellington was able to produce some of the most groundbreaking and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

A notable example of Ellington's innovative approach to sound is evident in his use of voice as an instrument, as illustrated in his early piece, Creole Love Call. This twelve bar blues, characterized by its slow and deliberate pace, features six distinct choruses, each showcasing Ellington's ability to complement the style of his soloists. The piece commences with a call and response between voice and reeds, with the voice beginning smoothly and melodically before transitioning to a rougher tone towards the end. This is followed by a muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes. Subsequent choruses feature a sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase, and a full band echo of the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections. The climactic fifth chorus sees the reeds initiating the call and response in a high register, supported by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections. The sixth and final chorus returns to the structure of the first, with call and response between voice and reeds, and in this instance, the voice takes on the sound of the "growl" technique, soloing as an instrument. A brief tag concludes the piece with a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is a hallmark of his work, as evident in subsequent compositions such as Hot and Bothered and It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing). In Hot and Bothered, Ellington seamlessly combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color, using a call and response phrase between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing to create a rich and complementary sound. Similarly, in It Don't Mean a Thing, Ellington employs Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton to great effect, introducing the melody on muted trombone in a way that showcases the unique qualities of Nanton's playing.

I'd been grappling with this unshakeable feeling of incompleteness since I was 14, when the world opened up and I found myself in the midst of teenage chaos. Three years later, at 17, I was still searching for something, though I'd narrowed it down to a desire for connection with someone rather than a mere object. Yet, I remained unimpressed by every boy who crossed my path, as if I was immune to the usual high school allure. I couldn't help but wonder what was behind this peculiarity, and I spent years mulling over various theories. But nothing ever added up, leaving me stuck in this cycle of self-doubt and curiosity.

My home life was a tranquil oasis amidst the turmoil. My parents were the epitome of calm and composure, rarely arguing with each other or with me – the only exceptions being when I pushed the boundaries of my independence and individuality. They were a peaceful couple, but I was the wild child in our household, bringing a spark of energy and playfulness that made me likable and admired by all who knew me.

But today was different. As I wandered through the house, searching for inspiration, the sound of my mother's distressed cry pierced the air, followed by the unmistakable tone of her voice. Panic set in as I sprinted towards the kitchen, my heart racing with every step. "Mom! Mom, what's wrong?!" I exclaimed, my voice trembling. I rushed into the room to find my mother lying on the ground, wincing in pain, her voice barely above a whisper. I dropped to her side, offering what little support I could. "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to... the hospital." The words tumbled out in short, labored breaths, and I knew she was in agony. "Okay, Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up," I said, trying to keep my voice steady. My mother directed me with her hands, and I was grateful for every ounce of strength I'd built up through yoga and exercise, which now allowed me to lift her and carry her to the car.

The hospital was a flurry of sterile smells and worried faces, but my focus was solely on my mother's well-being. I quickly settled her into the backseat and drove, my mind racing with worry. At the hospital, I rushed to get her help, calling out to the doctors as they quickly gathered around. Soon, a rolling bed appeared, and my mother was whisked away for immediate attention. I was left to sit, my anxiety simmering just below the surface.

As it turned out, my mother had slipped off a step stool while trying to retrieve a vase from the highest cabinet. It was a simple misstep, but one that had sent her tumbling to the ground.

It's a well-established fact that embracing the Mediterranean Diet, characterized by its emphasis on plant-based foods, monounsaturated fats, and moderate alcohol intake, can have a profound impact on our health. In fact, a plethora of studies have demonstrated that adhering to this diet can significantly reduce the risk of chronic heart disease and stroke. The study in question sheds light on the relationship between adherence to the "Mediterranean Diet" and the risk of heart-related issues, specifically chronic heart disease, stroke, and stroke mortality.

In essence, the Mediterranean Diet is a modified version of its precursor, with a greater focus on consuming plant-based proteins like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, while minimizing animal products and saturated fats. The results of prior studies have been promising, showcasing the diet's effectiveness in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. However, research has been lacking in the area of stroke and stroke mortality.

Our investigation involved analyzing data from the Nurses' Health Study, which included 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, with no prior history of cardiovascular disease or diabetes. Over a period of 20 years, from 1984 to 2004, we computed an "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score" based on self-reported food frequency questionnaires. These questionnaires underwent validation studies to ensure accuracy. We also accounted for various lifestyle factors, including body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and leisure-time physical activity.

To minimize random variation and better represent long-term dietary habits, we calculated cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated questionnaires. We adjusted for potential confounders like age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use. Our analysis revealed that a higher aMed diet score was associated with a lower risk of heart disease and stroke in the study participants. Specifically, women with the highest aMed quintile had a 29% lower risk of chronic heart disease and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile.

Fast forward to 2007, and it seemed like the world had hit rock bottom. The United States of America found itself in the midst of a devastating financial crisis. Joblessness skyrocketed, the housing market imploded, and many of America's largest corporations were left reeling. The question on everyone's lips was: how did this catastrophe unfold, and how can we prevent it from happening again? To put it bluntly, the financial crisis was the result of reckless and naive policy decisions that forced banks and firms to dispense sub-prime loans into a fragile financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were coerced into underwriting and repackaging these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were left scrambling for capital, and the chaos was transferred to the repackaged mortgages they'd sold, and ultimately, the entire economy.

Looking back, the roots of the crisis stretch as far back as 1999, during the Clinton administration. The President was eager to secure a second term, and his team relaxed lending restrictions to boost his popularity. This move set the stage for the impending sub-prime crisis seven years later. In 1999, Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported on the pressure being felt by Fannie Mae, the nation's largest home mortgage underwriter, to offer loans to low- and moderate-income individuals. The government-subsidized corporation was also under pressure to maintain its rapid profit growth. Holmes astutely foresaw the consequences of these actions, warning of a potential government rescue similar to the savings and loan industry debacle of the 1980s. As we now know, ill-advised lending would ultimately lead to a catastrophic economic meltdown.

A perfect storm of factors contributed to the economic freefall, including the complex and convoluted nature of modern mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were all extensively used in the years leading up to the crisis, intertwining various sectors of the economy with the housing market. U.S. households and financial markets as a whole became over-leveraged in the housing market, leaving them vulnerable to even the slightest price fluctuations.

The housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had invested in these mortgage-backed securities were left reeling. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007, which accounted for approximately 30% of the country's GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold at fire-sale prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to transition to commercial banks subject to intense regulatory oversight. Fannie and Freddie were in $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

I'll never forget that notorious section of my story where I'm tempted to unleash a torrent of exposition, stretching my writer's wings to impress, but often ending up putting my readers to sleep or sending them fleeing in frustration.  Dr. Merlin has been known to slam her monitor in exasperation when she finds herself stuck in a sea of Too Much Information, and I'm talking the not-very-fun kind.

Exposition is the enemy of a good story.

My fellow writers already know the age-old adage, "Show, don't tell," but I still find myself succumbing to lengthy passages where nothing happens or, worse, too much happens.  Exposition is that pesky inner voice urging me to tell the reader everything, from the history to the minutest details, to get to the good stuff (not to be confused with the inner voice whispering to reveal every character's backstory, no matter how insignificant).

Exposition is essentially regaling the audience with a straightforward account of what's happening, often in dry prose.  In film, this plays out when one character unloads a wealth of information on another, à la "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

Let's take an example.  When reading a story, I'm informed that the heroine met her beloved at a specific time and place, got married in a grand celebration, and witnessed her husband's tragic murder.  I wouldn't expect this entire sequence to take up two pages, with both characters only getting a few lines of dialogue.  I'd expect the author to spend some time developing the husband's character, showing through his words and actions how deeply he adored his wife, and I'd expect the heroine to reveal, through her thoughts and actions, how his presence enriched her life.  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow me to become emotionally invested in his fate and gain insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, the depth of their bond, and clues about her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams reflected through his eyes.  I'd mourn his loss with her, growing more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, I'd expect more substance behind the bare bones of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, it's my job to provide that substance.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, and presses on*)  Sometimes it's tempting to rush past certain details.  Perhaps I'm introducing a new character with a storied past: he used to be in the Air Force, now runs the night shift at a gas station, has been married twice, has no kids, loves fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the station someday, and starts his day with Eggs Benedict.

I caught two local broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio, the first of which was NBC 4's live newscast on August 13, 2011. The leading story was about a heinous crime: a man named Shad Hostettler had stabbed his wife, though her name wasn't mentioned. They aired his mugshot, and he looked like the embodiment of pure evil. The news team devoted about two minutes to the story, which was still unfolding. I think they allocated an adequate amount of airtime to this distressing event. 

The next story was about an early morning shooting involving 18-year-old Travis Buyers in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically injured, and no arrests had been made or suspects identified at the time. The SWAT team was on the scene, investigating the crime. This story seemed rather rushed, and I suspect it might have been due to the fact that the victim was a black man from a predominantly black neighborhood. It's a phenomenon I've observed for years: when minorities are victims of a crime, they often get shortchanged in the news coverage. In contrast, if a white child or adult is kidnapped or a victim of a crime, the media goes into overdrive; but when it's a minority person, they're lucky if they get a mention.

The next story dealt with a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. The news team provided details about the possible location of the incident, and it was determined that a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle had hit the aircraft. Crime-Stoppers offered a $5,000 reward for any information leading to the arrest of the shooter.

The next story focused on the impending rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They mentioned that the temperatures would remain in the mid-to-low eighties for the weekend. The brief length of this story was likely due to the anchor wanting to use it as a teaser to keep viewers engaged.

They also covered a story about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. The perpetrator was described as a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie sweatshirt and estimated to be around six feet tall and 150 pounds. I found it peculiar that they devoted so much attention to his racial description and how dark he was.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas-based marijuana kingpin who had conspired to distribute large quantities of the substance to Ohio. One thing that caught my attention was that instead of stating his 25-year prison sentence, they mentioned "300 months." I'm not sure if they thought that made it sound harsher or if it was just a stylistic choice. They also highlighted that he was a Hispanic man, but I'm not convinced it was relevant to the story.

There's a mystique surrounding brotherhood - an unbreakable bond that defies time and circumstance. Within its depths, a complex tapestry of emotions unfolds: love, pride, jealousy, cruelty, and more. Brothers have a unique understanding of one another, a connection that transcends the shallow relationships we form with others. When you look at your brother, you see a reflection of yourself, a truth that becomes glaringly evident in the most trying of times. This bond isn't always easy to navigate, and the emotions that accompany it come with a steep price. Understanding this fraternal link requires embracing the consequences that follow, and it's only when we can gaze into our brother's eyes that we truly see ourselves - not as others perceive us, but as we truly are. Our actions and their aftermath reveal our character, a truth that's difficult to confront but essential to growth.

The novel "The Scarlet Ibis" masterfully explores this theme, weaving a story of two brothers who navigate the intricate web of emotions tied to their bond. Against the backdrop of a lush, vivid landscape, these two boys embark on a futile journey, their relationship marked by bitter disappointment and intense pride. The climactic scene is a poignant example of this complex dynamic, and only one brother emerges unscathed. Through the protagonist's direct characterization and his interactions with his brother, as well as the narrator's nuanced perspective, we gain insight into the complex feelings that shape the protagonist's world and inform his actions.

At its core, the protagonist's actions are driven by one dominant emotion: pride. From their early adventures together to their final, fateful excursion, he grapples with resentment towards his little brother, Doodle. The protagonist had envisioned a brother who could share in his passions, a companion to explore the world with. He dreamed of racing to Horsehead Landing, perching in the top fork of the great pine, and learning the skills he'd mastered through trial and error. But Doodle's fragile health makes such exploits impossible, crushing the protagonist's fantasies and leaving him feeling bereft. The depth of his disappointment is evident in his disturbing thoughts of suffocating his brother, a bleak testament to the darkness that can lurk beneath the surface of even the most loving relationships. Yet, when Doodle smiles, the protagonist's heart softens, revealing a glimmer of hope and a love that's hard to deny. This dichotomy speaks to the complexity of brotherly love, a bond that's both beautiful and fraught with challenges.

We're constantly amazed by the intricate complexity of the human brain, that unpredictable and creative information-processing machine. As technology has evolved from its humble beginnings to the modern era, so too have the metaphors used to describe our brains. We've seen it likened to a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, a book, and most recently, a computer - each era's comparison shedding light on some aspect of its function. However, it's essential to remember that these analogies are helpful but limited, and can lead to misconceptions if taken too literally.

When it comes to processing information, it all starts with the sensory organs, which convert physical stimuli like touch, heat, sound waves, or light into electrical signals. These signals are continually transformed by the brain's algorithms through both bottom-up and top-down processing.
