Within its depths, a complex tapestry of emotions unfolds: love, pride, jealousy, cruelty, and more. Brothers have a unique understanding of one another, a connection that transcends the shallow relationships we form with others. When you look at your brother, you see a reflection of yourself, a truth that becomes glaringly evident in the most trying of times. This bond isn't always easy to navigate, and the emotions that accompany it come with a steep price. Understanding this fraternal link requires embracing the consequences that follow, and it's only when we can gaze into our brother's eyes that we truly see ourselves - not as others perceive us, but as we truly are. Our actions and their aftermath reveal our character, a truth that's difficult to confront but essential to growth.

The novel "The Scarlet Ibis" masterfully explores this theme, weaving a story of two brothers who navigate the intricate web of emotions tied to their bond. Against the backdrop of a lush, vivid landscape, these two boys embark on a futile journey, their relationship marked by bitter disappointment and intense pride. The climactic scene is a poignant example of this complex dynamic, and only one brother emerges unscathed. Through the protagonist's direct characterization and his interactions with his brother, as well as the narrator's nuanced perspective, we gain insight into the complex feelings that shape the protagonist's world and inform his actions.

At its core, the protagonist's actions are driven by one dominant emotion: pride. From their early adventures together to their final, fateful excursion, he grapples with resentment towards his little brother, Doodle. The protagonist had envisioned a brother who could share in his passions, a companion to explore the world with. He dreamed of racing to Horsehead Landing, perching in the top fork of the great pine, and learning the skills he'd mastered through trial and error. But Doodle's fragile health makes such exploits impossible, crushing the protagonist's fantasies and leaving him feeling bereft. The depth of his disappointment is evident in his disturbing thoughts of suffocating his brother, a bleak testament to the darkness that can lurk beneath the surface of even the most loving relationships. Yet, when Doodle smiles, the protagonist's heart softens, revealing a glimmer of hope and a love that's hard to deny. This dichotomy speaks to the complexity of brotherly love, a bond that's both beautiful and fraught with challenges.

We're constantly amazed by the intricate complexity of the human brain, that unpredictable and creative information-processing machine. As technology has evolved from its humble beginnings to the modern era, so too have the metaphors used to describe our brains. We've seen it likened to a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, a book, and most recently, a computer - each era's comparison shedding light on some aspect of its function. However, it's essential to remember that these analogies are helpful but limited, and can lead to misconceptions if taken too literally.

When it comes to processing information, it all starts with the sensory organs, which convert physical stimuli like touch, heat, sound waves, or light into electrical signals. These signals are continually transformed by the brain's algorithms through both bottom-up and top-down processing. To illustrate this, imagine looking at a picture of a black box against a white background. Bottom-up processing involves breaking down the image into basic components like color and orientation, ultimately determining that you're seeing a box. Meanwhile, top-down processing uses the results of earlier steps to speed up your recognition of the object, helping you decide whether it's a box or a hole in the background.

As information is processed to a certain point, an attention filter kicks in, deciding which signals are most important and which cognitive processes they should be routed to. For example, you may process every blade of grass when you glance down at your shoes, but your attention filter helps you tune them out. Conversely, you might pick out your name in a noisy room. This process repeats at various stages, with the results of processing influenced by attention at each step.

Before the brain can process information, it must first store it. There are three primary types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Information is first encoded, and different types of encoding suit different sensory stimuli. When it comes to verbal input, for instance, it can be encoded based on its structural appearance, phonetic sound, or semantic meaning. Once stored, information must be maintained, and research suggests that working memory, which holds information for about 20 seconds, relies on an electrical signal looping through a specific series of neurons for a short time. Long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain proteins.

There are numerous theories about how knowledge is organized within the brain, each with its unique perspective. Some are based on how humans retrieve memories, while others draw from computer science and neurophysiology. One such model is the semantic network, which proposes that concepts are represented by nodes and linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, the concept of "chair" might be connected to "table," which in turn is linked to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley's dystopian novel, Brave New World, serves as a scathing critique of the impending dangers of unchecked technological advancement and the capitalist system that perpetuates it. The novel depicts a society where people value collectivity above individuality, with its citizens conditioned from a young age to prioritize immediate gratification above all else. The characters are unwitting pawns in a grand game, trapped within a narrow ideology dictated by the all-powerful World Controller. When viewed through the lens of Marxist ideology, Huxley's work reveals a deep-seated distrust of the emerging economic systems of his time.

One of the primary targets of Huxley's satire is the capitalist system, which is reflected in his use of Marxist concepts such as homogeny and reification. These terms highlight the ways in which capitalist systems can lead to the suppression of individuality and the uniformity of the masses. The novel's depiction of the lower classes, known as Deltas and Gammas, is particularly telling, as they are conditioned to prioritize consumption and indulgence above all else, thanks to the pervasive use of hypnopædia. This manipulation is masterminded by the World Controller, who maintains a stranglehold on the lower classes through ideological control.

The concept of hegemony – where a dominant group exercises control over a subordinate group – is also evident in Brave New World. The upper classes, comprising Alphas and Betas, are born with the knowledge of this manipulation but do little to challenge it, further solidifying the grip of capitalism on the society. The novel's portrayal of relationships between characters is also noteworthy, as they are superficial and lack depth. This may suggest that the rise of technology and capitalism has stripped individuals of their free will and emotional expression, reducing love and other intense emotions to mere surface-level interactions.

The novel's characters often focus on physical appearance, with men commenting on women's physical attributes and women discussing their romantic conquests with little shame. This limited emotional landscape serves as a commentary on the socioeconomic effects of capitalism, where individuals are content with their place in the hierarchy and conform to societal expectations. Their unwavering obedience to the status quo is a testament to Marxist theories on the proletariat, who are conditioned to believe in their own superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform to the norms of their peers.

It's been about two and a half years since I stepped onto the University Park campus, and four and a half semesters of navigating its twists and turns have taught me that getting around can be a real challenge. As a freshman, I was stuck in an East Halls dorm room, the farthest I could get from the action without venturing onto the stadium or Bryce Jordan Center grounds. Commuting from Stuart Hall to classes in buildings like Willard, smack in the center of campus, was a 25-minute trek – and that was on a good day, weather permitting. But I've learned that it wasn't always this way. I spoke with an alum not much older than myself, who shared that the East Halls used to be isolated from the rest of the campus by a massive expanse of unused land. Fast-forward to today, and that open space has been transformed into sports fields, sleek new buildings like the Creamery and health services center, and rows of apartments. As the campus continues to sprawl, getting from one place to another is becoming increasingly difficult.

That's when I realized the obvious solution – the humble bicycle. But it's not just about having a bike; students need to actually ride them, and the campus needs to be designed with cyclists in mind. I chatted with a friend who'd taken a several-year break from biking, only to rediscover its joys. "Bikes are the way to go," he said. "For a while, it wasn't cool to ride, but it's the only way to get around." Not only is biking great exercise, but it's also the most efficient way to travel. With a hearty bowl of oatmeal and a bit of effort, you can cover 30 miles or more. As an off-campus student, I now live just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. Buying a bike was one of the smartest decisions I made this year. Classes in Thomas building, a 25-minute walk from my place, are a breeze to get to on two wheels – just 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The problem is, Pollock Road, the most direct route to Thomas, isn't always a bike-friendly stretch. Walking, on the other hand, is a viable option, but with my schedule, I just don't have the time. If I didn't have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option, sucking up an extra 30-40 minutes of my day – over two and a half hours every week. That's time I just can't afford to spare.
